  "text": "The base compositions of the 13 protein-coding genes are T > C > A > G. The proportions of the four bases have no apparent bias at the first codon position but have significant difference at the second and third positions. The percentage of T at the second position is up to 40.9% to 41.1%, but that of G is only 13.6% to 13.8%. In particular, G at the third position is only 9.6% to 12.5%, which is in agreement with previous reports [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ). There is a slight difference in codon usage among three rhombosoleids. The most frequently used amino acid is leucine (16.5% to 17.2%), while cysteine (0.7% to 0.8%) is the least frequently used. The level of homology of genes between the three rhombosoleid species ranges from 63% (ND2 gene) to 85% (COII gene). The similarity between C. nudipinnis and P. flavilatus is generally higher ",
